HEADWORD: Diesis
<hw>Di"e*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Dieses</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[NL., fr. Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ to
let go through, dissolve; <grk>dia`</grk> through + <?/ to let go,
send.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A small interval, less
than any in actual practice, but used in the mathematical calculation of
intervals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Print.)</fld> <def>The mark ⟦Dagger⟧; -- called
also <altname>double dagger</altname>. It is used in printing to
indicate a cross reference or footnote</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> double obelisk.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dies juridicus</ent>⟦br⟧
